Git has a pointer called HEAD.
HEAD points to the current branch.
The branch points to a commit.

git switch main

git switch -c feature/welcome-board
//new branch creation
-c means create
Without -c, git switch feature/welcome-board would only work if that branch already exists.


To confirm where HEAD is pointing
git branch

git add . moves all modified and new files from the working directory into the staging area.
It does not commit.
It prepares.
The . means “current directory and everything inside it.”
Without git add, git commit will not include your edits.
git commit -m "Add welcome instruction board feature"
creates an immutable snapshot of everything currently staged.
Mechanically:

• Git takes the staged file states
• Creates a new commit object
• Stores metadata (author, time, message)
• Moves the branch pointer forward to that new commit


git push -u origin feature/welcome-instruction-board
-u means --set-upstream
Pushes your local branch to the remote.
Links your local branch to that remote branch.

After this, future pushes can be simplified to:

git push
because Git now knows which remote branch it tracks.
Without -u, you would have to specify remote and branch every time.

When you cloned the repository or first connected it to GitHub, Git stored a remote name.
By default, that remote is called origin


git switch main

switching is not merging.

git switch main only moves HEAD to the main branch.
It changes which timeline you are standing on.
It does not combine anything.

git merge feature/welcome-instruction-board
